      "type": "theory",
      "id": "theory_hex_frac",
      "title": "Hexadecimal Fractions",
      "content": "Just like binary and decimal, hexadecimal can have fractions using a hex point!\n\n**Fractional Place Values (powers of 16 with negative exponents):**\n\u2022 16\u207b\u00b9 = 1/16 = 0.0625 (sixteenths place)\n\u2022 16\u207b\u00b2 = 1/256 = 0.00390625 (two-hundred-fifty-sixths place)\n\u2022 16\u207b\u00b3 = 1/4096 \u2248 0.000244 (and so on...)\n\n**Example 1: Convert 1.8 (hex) to decimal**\n\nHex:       1   .  8\nPositions: 1   .  1/16\nValues:    1      8 (8 in decimal)\nCalculate: 1\u00d71    8\u00d7(1/16)\nResults:   1  +   0.5 = 1.5\n\nSo 1.8 in hex = 1.5 in decimal!\n\n**Example 2: Convert A.4 (hex) to decimal**\n\nHex:       A   .  4\nValues:    10     4\nPositions: 1      1/16\nCalculate: 10\u00d71   4\u00d70.0625\nResults:   10 +   0.25 = 10.25\n\nSo A.4 in hex = 10.25 in decimal!\n\n**Example 3: Convert 0.C (hex) to decimal**\n\nHex:       0.  C\nValues:     .  12\nCalculate:     12\u00d7(1/16)\nResult:        0.75\n\nSo 0.C in hex = 0.75 in decimal!\n\n**Real-World Use: Color Precision**\nHex fractions aren't commonly used in everyday programming, but understanding them helps with:\n\u2022 Color interpolation\n\u2022 High-precision graphics\n\u2022 Understanding floating-point representation\n\u2022 Academic and theoretical computer science\n\n**Pro Tips:**\n\u2022 Convert letter digits (A-F) to 10-15 first\n\u2022 First fractional position is 1/16 = 0.0625\n\u2022 Hex fractions are more precise than decimal for some values\n\u2022 Each hex digit after point = 4 binary bits after binary point"
    },
